<br>
I mean .. we all like that at some level, else we wouldnt be playing at all, but it's better to have more options for improvement than that.<br>
<br>
I think level should matter far *less* in the game than it does atm. I think it's kinda sad that our whole guild is basically forcing our MT to level up from 60 to 65 because it will make a *huge* difference to our raid capability. He wanted to 'mess around' getting aa and getting better tradeskill gear, and we've basically guilted him into levelling ...<br>
<br>
Let me raise one other slightly related theory: I'm not convinced it's possible to produce a persistant multiplayer game that is both really fun and really balanced. I say persistant to exclude games where you start from the same fixed point every time you play eg card games or monopoly or such.<br>
<br>
In a persistant game I think a hell of a lot of fun comes from the fact you can do something a lot of other people cant (eg different classes or right click gear), and I reckon it's basically impossible to balance those completely. Even now clerics are desperately unhappy they are too wanted for raids, are totally unable to solo and are seeing their grouping 'wantedness' slowly degrading as tanks slowly gain ac and hp. Meanwhile melee are unable to solo, wanted for raids somewhat and for groups somewhat. Casters are good soloers (mostly), good groupers (mostly) and great raiders (mostly). Better balance? Probably. I dunno.<br>
<br>
Replace classes with 'skill trees' open to all and you still have to balance the different trees, unless you make all trees open to all on the grounds of fairness and you end up with an uninteresting state of everyone identical again. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=elasto>Elasto</A> at: 4/2/03 3:06:22 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=goladus>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<br>Err, Forum Arch Mage?</span><br>  Posts: 3774<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/2/03 3:32:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25564.topic&index=123>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://doug.feldmann.com/Sigurd.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Define &quot;exploit&quot;</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Unfair compared to what. Just becase something is unfair dosn't make it an exploit. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Acording to in game laws and mechanics it is perfectly fair.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Thus it is not a bug, thus it is not an exploit according to my defintion, even if it is unfair.  If you consider the mechanics to be operating contrary to design intent, then it is both bugged and unfair and therefore an exploit. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=goladus>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<br>Err, Forum Arch Mage?</span><br>  Posts: 3775<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/2/03 3:52:39 am)</font><br>  